
<h4>Validation of putative CRoPS SNPs</h4>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec3.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec3.p1"></a><p>Small-scale validation of putative SNPs was carried out using the SNPWave® technology <a href="#pone.0001172-VanEijk1">[24]</a>. From the selection of 591 putative SNPs mined according to the stringent criteria mentioned above (including a minimal of 12 bases flanking sequence surrounding the target SNP and minimal interval of 12 bases devoid of additional SNPs), 30 SNPs were randomly selected. Two 15-plex SNPWave assays were designed and tested using two parental lines and 94 recombinant inbred lines (RIL) offspring of the ISU (B73×Mo17) maize mapping population. For 23 out of 30 tested loci (77%) clear SNPWave reactions products were observed for both alleles, while for the remaining 7 loci one or both alleles were not observed (conversion failure). For all 23 SNP loci functioning properly in the SNPWave assay, the parental lines B73 and Mo17 were polymorphic and segregation was observed among RIL lines (<a href="#pone-0001172-g004">Fig. 4</a>), indicative of a high proportion of mined SNPs being derived from single-copy regions in the genome.</p>
